CM3015 Machine Learning and Neural Networks¶

Enhancing CIFAR-10 Image Classification Using Deep Learning¶

1. Introduction¶

The report utilizes the Universal Workflow of Machine Learning to produce a model that achieves the best results on the CIFAR-10 dataset. This is achieved through extensive experimentation exclusively using Dense and Dropout layers.

1.1 Background and Motivation¶

In the realm of computer vision, deep learning techniques have demonstrated remarkable performance in tasks such as image classification. The CIFAR-10 dataset, curated by Alex Krizhevsky, Vinod Nair, and Geoffrey Hinton, consisting of 60,000 32x32 color images across 10 classes, serves as a benchmark for evaluating the effectiveness of such techniques.Our motivation lies in exploring various methodologies to enhance image classification accuracy on this dataset.

1.2 Objectives of the Project¶

The primary objective is to develop a robust deep learning model for image classification on CIFAR-10. Specifically, we aim to:

  • Develop a baseline deep learning model for image classification on the CIFAR-10 dataset.
  • Investigate different model tuning techniques, including adjustments to model capacity, layer regularization, and dropout, to improve model performance.
  • Evaluate the effectiveness of these techniques in enhancing the accuracy of image classification.
  • Analyze the computational requirements and scalability of the models.
  • Discuss the ethical and social implications of using deep learning models for image classification.

1.3 Overview of the CIFAR-10 Dataset¶

The CIFAR-10 dataset comprises 60,000 color images divided into 10 classes, each containing 6,000 images. The dataset is further partitioned into 50,000 training images and 10,000 test images. Notably, the images are relatively low-resolution, with dimensions of 32x32 pixels, posing unique challenges for classification algorithms.

Source: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/ekaakurniawan/the-cifar10-dataset, The CIFAR-10 dataset used in this project was obtained from Kaggle. I acknowledge the contribution of Alex Krizhevsky in creating the dataset.

1.4 Scope and Structure of the Report¶

This report provides a comprehensive analysis of the project, starting with an overview of the CIFAR-10 dataset and the objectives of the project. The report is structured as follows:

  • Data Preprocessing: Describes the preprocessing steps applied to the CIFAR-10 dataset, including data cleaning, augmentation, normalization, and standardization.

  • Model Development: Discusses the architecture of the baseline model and the various model tuning techniques explored to enhance performance.

  • Model Evaluation: Evaluates the performance of different models using appropriate evaluation metrics and visualization techniques.

  • Discussion: Analyzes the results, discusses the implications of the findings, and explores potential avenues for future research.

  • Conclusion: Summarizes the key findings of the project and outlines its limitations and future directions.

2.1 Defining Hyperparameters¶

In this section, we define the default hyperparameters used for training the models. These hyperparameters include:

  • Epochs: The number of iterations over the entire dataset during training.
  • Batch Size: The number of samples processed before the model is updated.

These hyperparameters are crucial for controlling the training process and can significantly impact the performance and convergence of the model. By setting default values and allowing them to be overridden, the experimentation process becomes more flexible and adaptable to different scenarios.

2.3 Defining the Problem & Assembling the Dataset¶

Classifying raw images into categories is a fundamental task in computer vision with widespread applications across various industries. At its core, image classification aims to assign a single class label to an input image based on its visual content. This task falls under the domain of multi-class, single-label classification problems, where each image belongs to one of several predefined categories.

Formally, the process of image classification involves mapping an input image X to a predicted class label y using a model g parameterized by trainable parameters theta. Mathematically, this can be expressed as:

$\hat{y} = f(X) = \textbf{argmax } g(\theta, X)_{[k]}, \forall{k \in K=\{ 0...|classes| \}}$, where:

  • $X$ is the input image
  • $f$ is the labeller function
  • $g$ is the model
  • $\theta$ are the trainable parameters of the model

The present project focuses on utilizing the CIFAR-10 dataset, a well-known benchmark dataset widely used in the field of computer vision. The CIFAR-10 dataset, available in the TensorFlow Datasets Catalog, serves as an illustrative example of an image classification problem.

It consists of a collection of 60,000 32x32 color images distributed across 10 distinct classes, with each class containing 6,000 images. Specifically, the dataset comprises 50,000 training images and 10,000 test images, facilitating the evaluation of classification models.

2.4 Measure of Success¶

The effectiveness of a classification model is typically assessed using appropriate metrics that quantify its performance. In the context of the CIFAR-10 dataset, where the classes are balanced with an equal number of examples per class, accuracy serves as a suitable metric for evaluating model performance. Accuracy measures the proportion of correctly classified instances out of the total number of instances.

Mathematically, accuracy is calculated using the formula:

$Accuracy = \frac{Correct}{Total} = \frac{TP + TN}{TP + FP + TN + FN}$

where:

  • TP represents true positive predictions.
  • TN represents true negative predictions.
  • FP represents false positive predictions.
  • FN represents false negative predictions.

Additionally, to train a classification model, a suitable loss function is required to quantify the difference between predicted and actual class labels. Cross-entropy loss is commonly used for this purpose, especially in scenarios where the output of the model is a probability distribution over the classes. It measures the dissimilarity between the true probability distribution of the labels and the predicted probability distribution.

Mathematically, cross-entropy loss is calculated using the formula:

$CCE = L(y, \hat{y}) = -\sum^{N}_{n=1}\sum^{K}_{k=1} y_{nk} \log{\hat{y}_{nk}}$, where:

  • $y$ is a vector representing the one-hot encoded true label.
  • $\hat{y}$ is a vector representing the predicted probability distribution.
  • $N$ is the number of instances.
  • $K$ is the number of classes.

It is important to note that when using the categorical cross-entropy loss function, the true labels must be one-hot encoded. Alternatively, the sparse categorical cross-entropy loss function can be used, which does not require prior one-hot encoding of labels.

Below is a Python code snippet demonstrating the computation of categorical cross-entropy loss using TensorFlow:

In [12]:
# Initialize categorical cross-entropy loss

2.5 Evaluation Protocol¶

Hold-out test sets are an optimal strategy when the dataset is substantial, as is the case with the CIFAR10 dataset, which includes 10,000 data points exclusively for model evaluation.

Given this, the Evaluation Protocol chosen for this work is the Hold-out validation set.

The evaluation process follows these steps:

1. Dataset Splitting¶

  • The CIFAR10 dataset consists of 50,000 labeled examples in the CIFAR10_train split.
  • This split is further divided into two subsets: 80% for training (CIFAR10_train_train) and 20% for validation (CIFAR10_train_valid).

2. Training and Validation¶

  • During training, the model is trained on the CIFAR10_train_train split and validated on the CIFAR10_train_valid split.
  • The model's accuracy and loss are continuously monitored against both training and validation data during training.

3. Hyperparameter Tuning¶

  • Hyperparameters are tuned to prevent overfitting on the training split and to achieve the best accuracy on the validation split.
  • The best hyperparameters and model architecture are determined based on the lowest loss on the validation split.

4. Retraining¶

  • The best model architecture and hyperparameters are retrained from scratch using the entire CIFAR10_train split (train + valid) for the number of epochs that performed best during validation.

5. Final Evaluation¶

  • The model is evaluated on the held-out CIFAR10_test split, which was never used during training or validation.
  • The accuracy score on the CIFAR10_test split confirms whether the model generalizes well to unseen data.

3. Data Preprocessing & Preparation¶

3.1 Data Cleaning and Preprocessing Techniques¶

Data cleaning and preprocessing are crucial steps to ensure the quality and consistency of the dataset before training a machine learning model. In the context of the CIFAR-10 dataset, which consists of images, several preprocessing techniques can be applied to enhance the effectiveness of the model.

Removing Duplicate Images¶

This step aims to ensure that there are no duplicate images in the dataset, which could bias the model during training. The code iterates through the images, computes their hash values, and removes duplicates based on these hash values. The shapes of the original and cleaned datasets are printed for verification.

In [15]:
import cv2
from tensorflow.keras.datasets import cifar10
import hashlib

# Load CIFAR-10 dataset
(train_images, train_labels), (test_images, test_labels) = cifar10.load_data()

# Combine train and test sets for preprocessing
images = np.concatenate([train_images, test_images])
labels = np.concatenate([train_labels, test_labels])

# Convert images to C-contiguous format
images = np.ascontiguousarray(images)

# Step 1: Remove duplicate images
hashes = [hashlib.md5(img).digest() for img in images]
unique_hashes = set()
duplicate_indices = []
for i, h in enumerate(hashes):
    if h in unique_hashes:
        duplicate_indices.append(i)
    else:
        unique_hashes.add(h)

clean_images = np.delete(images, duplicate_indices, axis=0)
clean_labels = np.delete(labels, duplicate_indices, axis=0)

# Here, we are just printing the shapes to verify the removal of duplicates

print("Images:", images.shape)

3.2 Normalization and Standardization¶

Normalization and standardization are essential preprocessing steps to ensure that features have similar scales and distributions, which can improve the convergence and performance of machine learning models.

Normalization¶

Normalization scales feature values to a range between 0 and 1. The normalization formula typically involves subtracting the minimum value from each feature and then dividing by the range (the difference between the maximum and minimum values). This process ensures that all feature values fall within the same numerical range, making them comparable and preventing features with larger scales from dominating the model's training process.

In [20]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler, StandardScaler

# Perform normalization
scaler = MinMaxScaler()
images_normalized = scaler.fit_transform(images.reshape(-1, 32*32*3)).reshape(images.shape)

Standardization¶

This process transforms feature values to have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1. It helps center the data around zero and unit variance. Standardization is particularly useful when the features have different scales or follow a normal distribution.

In [21]:

3.2 Data Preparation¶

This code defines a Preprocessor class that preprocesses images and labels of the dataset. The purpose of this class is to transform the input images from their original format (32x32x3) into a flattened format (3072x1) and to one-hot encode the labels.

The preprocessing steps include:

  1. Scaling the RGB values of each image to the range [0, 1].

  2. Flattening the three RGB channels (32x32x3) into a single feature vector (3072x1).

  3. One-hot encoding the categorical labels, where all negative classes are marked as 0 and the positive class is marked as 1.

In [23]:
import tensorflow as tf

class Preprocessor:
    """
    Preprocesses the images of the dataset.

    :param image_dims: The number of pixels in the image (e.g., 32 * 32 * 3 for CIFAR-10).
    :param n_classes: The number of classes in the dataset.
    :return: A callable that takes an image and a label and preprocesses them.
    """

    def __init__(self, image_dims: int, n_classes: int):
        """
        Initializes the Preprocessor with image dimensions and number of classes.
        :param image_dims: The number of pixels in the image.
        :param n_classes: The number of classes in the dataset.
        """
        self.image_dims = image_dims
        self.n_classes = n_classes

    def __call__(self, image: tf.Tensor, label: tf.Tensor) -> tf.Tensor:
        """
        Performs preprocessing on the input image and label.
        :param image: The image tensor to preprocess.
        :param label: The label tensor to preprocess.
        :return: The preprocessed image and label tensors.
        """
        # If image data type is uint8 (8-bit unsigned integer), convert it to float32 and scale RGB values to [0, 1]
        if image.dtype == tf.uint8:
            image = tf.cast(image, tf.float32) / 255.0
            # Reshape image tensor to a flattened format
            image = tf.reshape(image, (self.image_dims,))
        # If label data type is int64 (64-bit integer), one-hot encode the labels
        if label.dtype == tf.int64:
            label = tf.one_hot(label, self.n_classes)
        return image, label

5. Baseline Model¶

The baseline model serves as the initial benchmark for performance evaluation in image classification tasks using the CIFAR-10 dataset. This model is designed to be simple yet effective enough to outperform a random classifier, providing a starting point for further model development and optimization.

5.1 Model Architecture¶

The baseline model is a feedforward neural network with a single hidden layer. It uses the Rectified Linear Unit (ReLU) activation function for the hidden layer and the softmax activation function for the output layer, which is typical for multi-class classification tasks. The number of units in the hidden layer is set to 10, corresponding to the number of classes in the CIFAR-10 dataset.

This script defines classes ModelBuilder for building neural network models and Experiment for conducting experiments with different models and datasets. The main function loads the CIFAR-10 dataset, defines a simple CNN model using ModelBuilder, and runs an experiment to train and evaluate the model. Finally, it plots the training and validation accuracy over epochs.

In [25]:
# Import necessary libraries and modules
from matplotlib.ticker import PercentFormatter
import itertools
import os

# Define the ModelBuilder class for constructing neural network models
class ModelBuilder:
    """
    Builder class for the Image Classification Model that minimizes
    a cross-entropy loss function (default) against the n_classes possible
    classes in the dataset, with the output head being a softmax layer.
    """

    # Define default optimizer, loss function, and other attributes
    optimizer: Union[str, optimizers.Optimizer] = "rmsprop"
    loss: Union[str, losses.Loss] = "categorical_crossentropy"
    log_dir_tensorboard: Optional[str] = None
    log_path_training: Optional[str] = None
    layers: List[
        Tuple[
            int,
            Optional[Union[str, Callable[[tf.Tensor], tf.Tensor]]],
            Optional[Union[str, regularizers.Regularizer]],
            Optional[float],
        ]
    ] = None

    def __init__(
        self,
        input_dims: int,
        n_classes: int,
    ):
        self.input_dims = input_dims
        self.n_classes = n_classes
        self.layers = []

    # Method to add a layer to the model
    def add_layer(
        self,
        units: int,
        activation: Optional[Union[str, Callable[[tf.Tensor], tf.Tensor]]] = None,
        regularization: Optional[Union[str, regularizers.Regularizer]] = None,
        dropout: Optional[float] = None,
    ) -> "ModelBuilder":
        """
        Adds a layer to the model.
        """
        self.layers.append((units, activation, regularization, dropout))
        return self

    # Method to set the optimizer
    def with_optimizer(
        self,
        optimizer: Union[str, optimizers.Optimizer],
    ) -> "ModelBuilder":
        """
        Sets the optimizer to use for training, or reverts to the default.
        """
        self.optimizer = optimizer
        return self

    # Method to set the loss function
    def with_loss(
        self,
        loss: Union[str, losses.Loss],
    ) -> "ModelBuilder":
        """
        Sets the loss function to use for training, or reverts to the default.
        """
        self.loss = loss
        return self

    # Method to build the model
    def build(self) -> models.Sequential:
        """
        Resets the tensorflow random seed, builds the model, compiles it,
        prints a summary of the model, and returns the model.
        """
        tf.keras.utils.set_random_seed(42)
        model = models.Sequential()
        for i, (u, a, r, d) in enumerate(self.layers):
            if i == 0:
                model.add(
                    layers.Dense(
                        u,
                        activation=a,
                        kernel_regularizer=r,
                        input_shape=(self.input_dims,),
                        name=f"x{i}",
                    )
                )
            else:
                model.add(
                    layers.Dense(
                        u,
                        activation=a,
                        kernel_regularizer=r,
                        name=f"x{i}",
                    )
                )
            if d is not None and d > 0.0:
                model.add(layers.Dropout(d))
        model.add(layers.Dense(self.n_classes, activation="softmax", name="y_hat"))
        model.compile(optimizer=self.optimizer, loss=self.loss, metrics=["acc"])
        model.summary()
        return model

Experimental Setup¶

The code also includes classes for conducting experiments in a standardized manner. The 'ModelBuilder' class facilitates the construction of neural network models with customizable architectures, while the 'Experiment' class orchestrates the training and evaluation process. The 'plot_history' function is provided for visualizing the training and validation performance over epochs.

In [26]:
# Define the Experiment class for conducting experiments
class Experiment:
    """
    Builds an experiment setup to the default hyperparameters, and
    run it against a given model, dataset, and preprocessor.
    """

    # Define attributes and initialize experiment setup
    train_data: tfds.Split
    valid_data: Optional[tfds.Split] = None
    preprocessor: Optional[Preprocessor] = None
    log_tensorboard_dirpath: Optional[str] = None
    log_csv_filepath: Optional[str] = None

    def __init__(self, default_hyperparams: Dict[str, Any], **kwargs):
        self.batch_size = kwargs.get("batch_size", default_hyperparams["batch_size"])
        assert self.batch_size > 0, "The `batch_size` must be greater than zero."
        self.epochs = kwargs.get("epochs", default_hyperparams["epochs"])
        assert self.batch_size > 1, "The `epochs` must be greater than 1."

    # Method to set the preprocessor
    def with_preprocessor(self, preprocessor: Optional[Preprocessor]) -> "Experiment":
        """
        Sets the preprocessor to use for training, or reverts to the default.
        """
        self.preprocessor = preprocessor
        return self

    # Method to set the model
    def with_model(self, model: models.Sequential) -> "Experiment":
        """
        Sets the model to use for training.
        """
        self.model = model
        return self

    # Method to set the training data
    def with_train_data(self, split: tfds.Split) -> "Experiment":
        """
        Sets the training data to use for training.
        """
        self.train_data = split
        return self

    # Method to set the validation data
    def with_valid_data(self, split: Optional[tfds.Split]) -> "Experiment":
        """
        Sets the validation data to use for validation.
        """
        self.valid_data = split
        return self

    # Method to enable logging to TensorBoard
    def enable_log_tensorboard(self, dirpath: str) -> "Experiment":
        """
        Enables logging to TensorBoard and sets the directory path to use.
        """
        self.log_tensorboard_dirpath = dirpath
        return self

    # Method to enable logging to CSV
    def enable_log_csv(self, filepath: str) -> "Experiment":
        """
        Enables logging to CSV and sets the file path to use.
        """
        filedir = os.path.dirname(filepath)
        if not os.path.isdir(filedir):
            os.makedirs(filedir)
        self.log_csv_filepath = filepath
        return self

    # Method to run the experiment
    def run(self) -> callbacks.History:
        """
        Runs the experiment, pre-processing the data if a preprocessor is set,
        and logging to TensorBoard and CSV if enabled.
        """
        assert self.model, "The `model` is required."
        assert self.train_data, "The `train_data` is required."
        train_xy = self.train_data
        valid_xy = self.valid_data
        if self.preprocessor:
            train_xy = train_xy.map(self.preprocessor)
            if valid_xy:
                valid_xy = valid_xy.map(self.preprocessor)
        train_xy = train_xy.cache().batch(self.batch_size)
        if valid_xy:
            valid_xy = valid_xy.cache().batch(self.batch_size)
        tf.keras.utils.set_random_seed(42)
        return self.model.fit(
            train_xy,
            epochs=self.epochs,
            batch_size=self.batch_size,
            validation_data=valid_xy,
            callbacks=self._build_callbacks(),
        )

    # Method to build callbacks for logging
    def _build_callbacks(self) -> Optional[List[callbacks.Callback]]:
        fit_callbacks = None
        if self.log_tensorboard_dirpath or self.log_csv_filepath:
            fit_callbacks = []
            if self.log_tensorboard_dirpath:
                fit_callbacks.append(
                    callbacks.TensorBoard(
                        log_dir=self.log_tensorboard_dirpath, write_graph=True, write_images=True
                    )
                )
            if self.log_csv_filepath:
                fit_callbacks.append(callbacks.CSVLogger(filename=self.log_csv_filepath))
        return fit_callbacks

# Define a function to plot the training and validation history
def plot_history(history: callbacks.History) -> None:
    metrics = history.history
    acc_train, acc_valid = metrics["acc"], metrics["val_acc"]
    loss_train, loss_valid = metrics["loss"], metrics["val_loss"]
    x = range(1, len(acc_train) + 1)
    fit = np.argmin(loss_valid)

    _, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2, sharex=True, sharey=False, figsize=(15, 5))
    axes[0].plot(x, loss_train, "ro", label="Loss (train)")
    axes[0].plot(x, loss_valid, "r", label="Loss (valid)")
    axes[0].annotate(
        f"fit boundary\n- epoch={fit}\n- loss={round(loss_valid[fit], 5)}",
        xy=(fit, loss_valid[fit]),
        xytext=(
            len(acc_train) * 0.5,
            max(itertools.chain(*[loss_train, loss_valid])) * 0.9,
        ),
        bbox=dict(boxstyle="round", fc="#ccc", ec="#444"),
        arrowprops=dict(
            facecolor="black",
            arrowstyle="->",
            connectionstyle="angle3,angleA=-45,angleB=70",
        ),
    )
    axes[1].set_ylim(-0.1, 1.1)
    axes[1].plot(x, acc_train, "go", label="Accuracy (train)")
    axes[1].plot(x, acc_valid, "g", label="Accuracy (valid)")
    axes[1].yaxis.set_major_formatter(PercentFormatter(xmax=1.0, decimals=0))
    axes[1].annotate(
        f"fit boundary\n- epoch={fit}\n- acc={round(acc_valid[fit], 5)}",
        xy=(fit, acc_valid[fit]),
        xytext=(
            len(acc_train) * 0.5,
            min(itertools.chain(*[acc_train, acc_valid])) * 0.1,
        ),
        bbox=dict(boxstyle="round", fc="#ccc", ec="#444"),
        arrowprops=dict(
            facecolor="black",
            arrowstyle="->",
            connectionstyle="angle3,angleA=45,angleB=-70",
        ),
    )
    for ax in axes:
        ax.axvline(fit, color="b")
        ax.legend()
        ax.grid()

Training Loss: Started at 2.3070 and gradually decreased to 1.9159.

Training Accuracy: Started at 9.88% and increased to 25.84%.

These results indicate that while the model's performance improved over the course of training, it still exhibits limited predictive power. Further model iterations and optimization techniques may be necessary to achieve higher accuracy on the CIFAR-10 dataset.

6. Scalling Up: Overfitting Model¶

To create a model that overfits the train split, we can experiment with models with larger capacities. This typically involves increasing the number of layers and/or the number of units in each layer. Let's start by visualizing the training and validation accuracy of the models experimented upon during part 5. This will help us understand the current performance before attempting to overfit the training data.

batch epochs optimizer $\alpha$ L1(u) L1(a) L1(r) L1(d) L2(u) L2(a) L2(r) L2(d) fit/epoch last/acc(train) fit/acc(valid)
512 100 rmsprop 0.001 256 relu - - 256 relu - - 39 71.56% 47.87%

512 100 rmsprop 0.001 4096 relu - - 4096 relu - - 28 90.42% 47.37%

We can see that as the model capacity increases, the training accuracy tends to improve while the validation accuracy may decrease, indicating potential overfitting.

Next, we can proceed with experimenting on models with even larger capacities to intentionally induce overfitting on the training data. We can add more layers or increase the number of units in existing layers. After training these models, we can observe the behavior of the training and validation accuracy curves to confirm overfitting.

7. Regularization and Model Tuning¶

In the model tuning step of the Universal Workflow, we aim to optimize model performance by carefully adjusting various aspects of the model. This involves understanding the boundaries set by the Baseline Model and the largest Overfitting Model, and then implementing changes to mitigate overfitting while maintaining high accuracy.

  1. Model Capacity (Layers and Units):
  • Adjusting the number of layers and units in the model impacts the complexity of the learned function.
  • A model with too few layers or units may underfit, while a model with too many may overfit.
  • The goal is to find the right balance where the model's capacity is sufficient to capture the underlying patterns in the data without memorizing noise.
  1. Layer Regularization:
  • Regularization techniques such as L2 regularization penalize large coefficients (weights and biases), promoting smoother transitions between layers.
  • By reducing the complexity of the learned function, regularization helps prevent overfitting to the training data.
  1. Layer Dropout:
  • Dropout is a regularization technique where random perceptrons are disabled during training.
  • This prevents any single perceptron from becoming overly influential, leading to more robust representations.
  • Adjusting the dropout rate introduces a regularization effect on the network, mitigating overfitting.
  1. Hyperparameter Tuning:
  • Changing the model architecture affects the parameter search space, necessitating updates to hyperparameters.
  • Hyperparameter tuning involves adjusting parameters such as the learning rate () to optimize the training process.
  • Proper tuning helps the model navigate the parameter space effectively, avoiding local minima and achieving better accuracy.

The following consequences are expected:

  • Reduced capacity, regularisation, dropout may all lead to drop in training accuracy demonstrating that the ability of the model to learn from the input is reduced.Training accuracy must then be returned to as close as possible to the Overfitting Model;

  • As soon as regularisation starts working, overfitting to the training data is postponed to later epochs. This might require the training to be extended over more epochs. However the loss for both train and valid start converging for longer, allowing the valid accuracy to increase at the same time that the train accuracy increases at a slower rate.

  • Finally, the exploration of the parameter search surface requires the adjustment of the (or, "learning rate"), which will cause the gradient descent to avoid local minima while pursuing deeper minima that produce better accuracy.

Dropout Regularization¶

Dropout regularization is implemented to prevent overfitting by randomly disabling a fraction of neurons during training. A single hidden layer with 2048 units and ReLU activation function is augmented with dropout regularization at a rate of 0.5.

Dropout is a regularization technique used to prevent overfitting by randomly dropping out (setting to zero) a fraction of input units during training, which helps to reduce co-adaptation of neurons.

Interpretation Of Results¶

Let's analyze the findings,

RMSprop Optimizer:¶

Models trained with the RMSprop optimizer at a learning rate () of 0.001 exhibit varying validation accuracies.

Without any regularization (L1 or L2) or dropout, the validation accuracy stands at 46.44% for a single-layer model with 2048 units and ReLU activation.

Introducing L2 regularization to this model slightly decreases validation accuracy to 38.15%.

Applying L1 regularization with a sparsity level of 50% yields a higher validation accuracy of 49.80%.

Adam Optimizer:¶

Models trained with the Adam optimizer demonstrate improved validation accuracies compared to RMSprop.

For instance, with a learning rate of 0.0001, validation accuracy reaches 50.45% without any regularization.

Increasing the number of epochs from 100 to 225 further improves the validation accuracy to 53.58%.

Effect of Model Capacity and Regularization:¶

Increasing model capacity by doubling the number of units to 4096 under Adam optimizer and L2 regularization leads to a validation accuracy of 53.32%.

However, excessively increasing model capacity without adequate regularization can lead to overfitting, as seen in the case of RMSprop with 50% L2 regularization, where the validation accuracy drops significantly to 26.39%.

Hyperparameter Tuning with Adam Optimizer:¶

Tuning hyperparameters like the learning rate can significantly impact model performance. A higher learning rate of 0.01 results in a validation accuracy of 25.65%, while a lower learning rate of 0.0001 yields better performance with accuracies exceeding 50%.

Comparison with Adadelta Optimizer:¶

Models trained with the Adadelta optimizer generally exhibit lower validation accuracies compared to Adam, even with the same hyperparameters and regularization settings.

For instance, with 225 epochs and L2 regularization, Adam achieves a validation accuracy of 53.58%, whereas Adadelta achieves 41.31%.

In summary, the validation accuracies vary across different configurations, indicating the importance of hyperparameter tuning, regularization techniques, and choice of optimizer in deep learning model training. Models with lower learning rates, appropriate regularization, and sufficient capacity tend to achieve higher validation accuracies, highlighting the significance of careful experimentation and optimization in model development.

8. Final Model¶

The Final Model stands as the pinnacle of our endeavor to strike an optimal balance between model complexity, performance, and computational efficiency. Through a meticulous process of exploration, experimentation, and fine-tuning, we have arrived at a model architecture that demonstrates promising performance on the CIFAR-10 dataset while ensuring generalization to unseen data.

Model Selection Procedure¶

The journey towards the Final Model commenced with the selection of the best architecture and hyperparameters. After exhaustive experimentation, a model architecture comprising two hidden layers, each housing 2048 units with ReLU activation function, L2 regularization, and a dropout rate of 20% emerged as the most effective configuration. This architecture was chosen based on its ability to strike a balance between model complexity and performance.

Subsequently, the Final Model underwent training on the entire CIFAR-10 training dataset for 225 epochs, a duration determined by the fit boundary established during fine-tuning. This exhaustive training regimen aimed to extract intricate patterns from the data while mitigating the risk of overfitting.

Results and Performance Evaluation¶

Evaluation on Hold-out CIFAR-10 Test Dataset: Following training, the Final Model's performance was evaluated against the hold-out CIFAR-10 test dataset to assess its generalization ability.

9. Analytical Insights¶

While the Final Model's performance on unseen data achieved an accuracy of only 54.24% in a task that humans typically excel at, it may not be suitable for real-world applications. However, the experimentation process yielded valuable insights that contribute to the understanding of model optimization and performance enhancement.

Key Insights¶

  1. Improvements Over Baseline Model: Departing from the simplistic baseline model, our journey toward the Final Model involved intricate techniques such as fine-tuning of densely connected layers, regularization, and hyperparameter tuning. These adjustments yielded a substantial enhancement, with the Final Model achieving nearly double the accuracy of the original model.

  2. Effectiveness of L2 Regularization: L2 regularization emerged as a powerful tool in combating overfitting, thereby enhancing the model's generalization ability. The consistent train and validation losses observed throughout the training process underscore the efficacy of this regularization technique.

  3. Optimal Dropout Rate: Our experimentation revealed that a dropout rate of 20% outperformed both no dropout and a more aggressive dropout rate of 50%. This finding underscores the delicate balance required in dropout regularization to prevent overfitting without compromising model performance.

  4. While the Adadelta optimizer exhibited steady loss reduction during training, it struggled to converge within a reasonable timeframe. As a result, the Adam optimizer, with its superior computational efficiency and convergence within 225 epochs, was selected for the Final Model.

Recommendations for Future Research:¶

  1. Utilization of Convolutional Layers: Integration of convolutional layers into the model architecture could address limitations associated with densely connected layers, potentially improving accuracy, especially in scenarios with limited datasets.

  2. Data Augmentation: Augmenting training data through techniques such as mirroring, rotation, and cropping holds the potential to enhance the representativeness of high-level features, thereby improving model performance, particularly in recognizing complex patterns.

  3. Further Exploration with Adadelta: Despite its challenges in convergence, allowing the Adadelta optimizer to train until convergence, possibly with enhanced computing resources, may unveil its full potential in achieving deeper loss. However, the marginal gains in accuracy must be weighed against increased computational costs.

10. Conclusion¶

In conclusion, the Final Model represents a significant leap forward in model optimization and performance enhancement. While achieving commendable accuracy on the CIFAR-10 dataset, there remains ample room for further research and refinement. By leveraging advanced techniques such as convolutional layers and data augmentation, future models can strive for even greater accuracy and robustness in tackling complex tasks. Our journey underscores the iterative nature of model development, where each experiment and insight contributes to the collective understanding, paving the way for advancements in machine learning and artificial intelligence.
